<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="62" type="distinguishing characters">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="62">Distinguishing characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="62">
Species of the nominotypical subgenus can be separated by all tarsal claws with a basal tooth of variable size, or in males the outer claw of mesotarsi is with small tooth or simple. They also have subcircular to subtriangular body and are more convex in comparison to most other subgenera except 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Charidotella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Charidotella (Metrionaspis)" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Metrionaspis">Metrionaspis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Charidotella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Charidotella (Chapadacassis)" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Chapadacassis">Chapadacassis</taxonomicName>
subgen. n. Otherwise the nominotypical subgenus is polymorphic displaying greater variability and some species externally reminds other subgenera. Most species are yellow with or without pattern on the ventral side of the elytral disc which can be variable. After revising most species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Charidotella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Charidotella" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Charidotella</taxonomicName>
there is no species in the nominotypical subgenus with dark annulus on the upper side of the elytra and all such coloured species are here transferred to 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xenocassis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" lsidName="Xenocassis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Xenocassis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
